## Consolidated Information Type Impact Table

| Information Type | Provisional C/I/A | Adjusted C/I/A | Adjustment Rationale |
|---|---|---|---|
| Patient Identity & Demographics | M/M/M | H/H/M | PHI context; identity theft risk; care continuity |
| Clinical Health Records | M/M/M | H/H/H | Highest sensitivity PHI; direct care safety implications |
| Laboratory & Diagnostic Results | M/M/M | H/H/M | Sensitive PHI; direct clinical decision input |
| User Account & Access Control | M/M/M | M/H/M | Access control integrity = system-wide security |
| Audit Logs | M/M/L | M/H/M | Log integrity required for accountability; HIPAA |
| Billing & Financial Information | M/M/L | H/M/L | PHI when combined with diagnosis codes; fraud risk |
| System Configuration | L/M/L | L-M/H/M | Configuration integrity affects clinical safety and security |
| De-Identified Analytics | L/L/L | L-M/L/L | Re-identification risk is context-dependent |

**High watermark across all information types: Confidentiality — High | Integrity — High | Availability — High**

This confirms the overall system categorization of **HIGH** established on Day 29 and provides the information-type-level evidentiary basis for that categorization.

