## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2015 Anthem breach** — which I covered earlier in this project — but want to revisit with a specific focus on information type scope.

One of the notable aspects of the Anthem breach is that the exposed data included not just traditional clinical records but the full breadth of member identity and demographic information: names, Social Security numbers, dates of birth, addresses, employment information, and income data. The breach affected approximately 79 million people, many of whom were not current patients but were enrolled members whose data Anthem maintained for administrative purposes.

The Anthem case is a useful reminder that information type identification needs to be comprehensive — not just the obvious clinical data, but all categories of information the system holds. Organizations that focus their security programs on protecting the most obviously sensitive data while underinvesting in protection of "administrative" data create the exact gap that the Anthem breach exploited. Demographic and identity information — often classified as lower sensitivity than clinical records — enabled identity theft and fraud at massive scale when exposed.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the information type inventory deliberately includes all eight categories rather than focusing only on clinical health records. The patient identity and billing information — sometimes treated as less sensitive than diagnoses and medications — carries real harm potential when exposed and warrants the same structural protections as the more obviously sensitive clinical data.

