## What I Am Still Thinking About

The re-identification risk question for de-identified analytics data is something I want to understand more technically. HIPAA provides two methods for de-identification — the Safe Harbor method (removing a defined list of 18 identifiers) and the Expert Determination method (a statistical analysis demonstrating that the risk of re-identification is very small). 

In practice, researchers have demonstrated that even Safe Harbor de-identified data can sometimes be re-identified when cross-referenced with other available datasets. A 2000 study by Latanya Sweeney demonstrated that 87% of the US population could be uniquely identified using only ZIP code, birth date, and sex — three data points that the Safe Harbor method does not require to be removed in full.

For a small clinic like MyClinic, the population served may be small enough that aggregate reports about rare conditions could effectively identify individuals even without any direct identifiers. I want to develop a more concrete understanding of when de-identification is genuinely protective versus when it provides false assurance of low sensitivity — because that distinction matters for access control and sharing decisions involving analytics data.

